1. Lists
Unordered Lists
Use asterisks, plus signs, or hyphens for bullet points.

```
- Item 1
- Item 2
  - Subitem 2.1
  - Subitem 2.2
- Item 3
```

produce 

- Item 1
- Item 2
  - Subitem 2.1
  - Subitem 2.2
- Item 3

---

Ordered Lists

Use numbers followed by a period.

```
1. First item
2. Second item
   1. Subitem 2.1
   2. Subitem 2.2
3. Third item
4. Links
```

produce 

1. First item
2. Second item
   1. Subitem 2.1
   2. Subitem 2.2
3. Third item
4. Links

----

Internal Links
You can link to sections within the same document using anchor links.

```
[Go to Section 2](#header-2)
```

produce 

[Go to Section 2](#header-2)

---
```
| Kind of           |            Syntax               |          Description          |
| ------------------| ------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
|  Internal Links       |[Go to Section 2](#header-2) | [Go to Section 2](#header-2) |
```
produce

| Kind of           |            Syntax               |          Description          |
| ------------------| ------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
|  Internal Links       |[Go to Section 2](#header-2) | [Go to Section 2](#header-2) |

External Links
Link to external websites.

```
[wikipedia](https://wikipedia.com)
```
produce

[wikipedia](https://wikipedia.com)

1. Images
You can include images using a similar syntax to links.

```
![Alt text](../../images/favicon.ico)
```
produce

![Alt text](../../images/favicon.ico)

1. Blockquotes
Use the > symbol for blockquotes.

```
> This is a blockquote.
> It can span multiple lines.
```

1. Code

Inline Code

Use backticks for inline code snippets.

```
This is `inline code`.
```
produce 
This is `inline code`.

---

Code Blocks

Use triple backticks for multi-line code blocks. You can specify the language for syntax highlighting.
Here is an example JavaScript code snippet (ignore **backslash** -   `\`) in the code snippet below:

```markdown
\```javascript
function helloWorld() {
    console.log("Hello, World!");
}
\```
```


produce

```javascript
function helloWorld() {
    console.log("Hello, World!");
}
```

